<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900518-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>900518-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Tokyo Investigating   Trades in Bank Stock   Prior to Market News</HL><DATE>05/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   JAPAN</CO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange and the Finance Ministrysaid they are investigating share trading in Long-Term CreditBank of Japan Ltd. ahead of a stock-split announcement.   Officials at the exchange and the ministry, which shareresponsibility for conducting inquiries under the country'syear-old insider-trading law, described their investigationsas routine. A stock-exchange official said he doesn't believethe investigation would produce evidence of insider trading,but an official at the ministry noted that the governmentdoesn't normally pursue stock-market investigations unlessthey see unusual dealings.</LP><TEXT>   The bank's share price began to climb sharply Tuesday onheavy volume. Trading in the stock was suspended by theexchange Wednesday morning, just before the bank announced a1-for-10 share split. The stock split is effective Aug. 11.   Before they were suspended, Long-Term Credit Bank's shareprice had jumped to 21,500 yen (US$141.76) from 19,500 yen($128.57) a day earlier. Volume surged to 116,900 shares,more than five times the daily average of the previous month.   A spokesman for Long-Term Credit Bank said he knew of noinvestigation centering on improper trading in the bank'sshares. He denied the possibility of insider trading, sayingthe bank was meticulous in the disclosure of informationabout the share split.   There have been no prosecutions under the insider-tradinglaw, which imposed the first legal sanctions on the practicehere.</TEXT></DOC>